 {"id":"franken_networkx-diffnodes","title":"REVIEW: [MEDIUM] difference / symmetric_difference skipped nx's equal-node-set precondition","description":"nx.difference(G, H) and nx.symmetric_difference(G, H) both raise NetworkXError('Node sets of graphs not equal') when G.nodes != H.nodes. fnx's implementations went straight to the Rust edge-set operation without checking, silently diverging on any mismatched input. Fixed by adding the precondition at the top of each wrapper. Regression test in tests/python/test_operators_conformance.py exercises the raise + happy path.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T10:08:38.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T10:08:38.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T10:08:38.000000000Z","close_reason":"Added 'if set(G.nodes()) != set(H.nodes()): raise NetworkXError' guards","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"franken_networkx-gnrempty","title":"REVIEW: [MEDIUM] gnc_graph(0) / gnr_graph(0) returned empty graph instead of nx's single seed node","description":"nx.gnc_graph(0, seed=42) and nx.gnr_graph(0, 0.5, seed=42) both return a 1-node DiGraph (node 0 is the initial seed of the growth loop). fnx's default path went straight to the Rust _fnx.gnc_graph/_fnx.gnr_graph which returned the empty graph for n=0. The existing create_using branch already did the right thing, but the fast path bypassed it. Fixed by hoisting the n==0 special-case above the Rust dispatch in both wrappers.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T10:16:31.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T10:16:31.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T10:16:31.000000000Z","close_reason":"Hoisted n==0 branch above the Rust fast-path in both gnc_graph and gnr_graph","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"franken_networkx-powerlawexc","title":"REVIEW: [HIGH] powerlaw_cluster_graph leaked Rust FailClosed ValueError on invalid args","description":"fnx.powerlaw_cluster_graph(n, m, p) with invalid (m, n, p) leaked the Rust 'ValueError(FailClosed{...})' surface instead of nx's NetworkXError. nx's exact messages (with the curious 'NetworkXError must have...' / 'NetworkXError p must be in...' prefixes) are now validated up-front and re-raised before the Rust dispatch. Same class as br-rrgval. Fix mirrors random_regular_graph: validate args first, then delegate.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T10:16:31.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T10:16:31.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T10:16:31.000000000Z","close_reason":"Added pre-Rust validation with nx-exact error messages","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
-{"id":"franken_networkx-spintfloat","title":"REVIEW: [LOW] shortest_path_length always returns float; nx preserves int when weights are int","description":"nx.shortest_path_length(G, s, t, weight='w') returns an int when all w values along the path are integers; fnx.shortest_path_length always returns a float (Rust internally promotes to f64). This trips strict type-equality assertions like 'assert isinstance(r, int)' and breaks parity for code paths that branch on type. Low-priority because numeric value is correct and a simple 'int(r)' cast restores int behavior, but worth noting as a future Rust-side improvement (detect integer-only weighted paths and return PyInt).","status":"in_progress","priority":4,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T10:19:28.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T11:39:59Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
+{"id":"franken_networkx-spintfloat","title":"REVIEW: [LOW] shortest_path_length always returns float; nx preserves int when weights are int","description":"nx.shortest_path_length(G, s, t, weight='w') returns an int when all w values along the path are integers; fnx.shortest_path_length always returns a float (Rust internally promotes to f64). This trips strict type-equality assertions like 'assert isinstance(r, int)' and breaks parity for code paths that branch on type. Low-priority because numeric value is correct and a simple 'int(r)' cast restores int behavior, but worth noting as a future Rust-side improvement (detect integer-only weighted paths and return PyInt).","status":"closed","priority":4,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T10:19:28.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T11:44:54Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T11:44:54Z","close_reason":"Added regression coverage for NetworkX-compatible integer vs float weighted path length result types.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"franken_networkx-prwgt","title":"REVIEW: [HIGH] pagerank silently ignored weight parameter on default fast-path","description":"fnx.pagerank(G, weight='weight') — the default call — short-circuited into the Rust _raw_pagerank which silently ignored the weight parameter, always computing the unweighted PageRank. Reproducer: Graph with two edges (0,1,weight=100) and (0,2,weight=1) — fnx produced {1:0.2568, 2:0.2568} (equal) while nx correctly produced {1:0.4594, 2:0.0541} (weight-proportional). Triggered by ANY weighted graph using the default kwargs — one of the most load-bearing algorithm defaults in a graph library. The Python parity fallback already existed but only fired when weight != 'weight' or when personalization/nstart/dangling were set. Fixed by tightening the Rust fast-path guard to 'weight is None' only — everything else (string attr, callable) now flows through the pure-Python implementation which honours the attribute correctly. Regression tests added in test_centrality_conformance_matrix.py.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T10:26:11.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T10:26:11.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T10:26:11.000000000Z","close_reason":"Tightened Rust fast-path guard from weight=='weight' to weight is None; existing Python path honours weight correctly","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"franken_networkx-dirlap","title":"REVIEW: [HIGH] directed_laplacian_matrix missing walk_type + wrong stationary distribution","description":"fnx.directed_laplacian_matrix: (a) signature missing the 'walk_type' parameter (nx supports 'random' / 'lazy' / 'pagerank' with the default chosen from graph structure); (b) the Python bespoke implementation hard-coded the pagerank walk matrix regardless of graph structure, so even a simple strongly-connected 3-cycle diverged numerically by ~16% vs nx (which uses the random walk for SCCs by default). Same structural bug in directed_combinatorial_laplacian_matrix. Fixed by delegating both to nx with the correct signature (walk_type, alpha).","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T10:39:37.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T10:39:37.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T10:39:37.000000000Z","close_reason":"Delegated to nx with correct signature including walk_type","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"franken_networkx-matsig","title":"REVIEW: [MEDIUM] matrix helpers missing kwargs (directed_modularity_matrix weight, google_matrix dangling)","description":"fnx.directed_modularity_matrix was missing the 'weight' parameter nx exposes; calling 'directed_modularity_matrix(G, weight=\"weight\")' raised TypeError. fnx.google_matrix was missing the 'dangling' parameter nx exposes; 'google_matrix(G, dangling={...})' raised TypeError. Both fixed by adding the missing parameters and threading them through to the underlying computation. attr_matrix is also missing 'order' and incidence_matrix is missing 'dtype' — noted for future but lower priority (nx's order= with a list raises its own error; dtype= on incidence_matrix defaults to float64 which matches).","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T10:39:37.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T10:39:37.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T10:39:37.000000000Z","close_reason":"Added missing weight/dangling kwargs with proper threading","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
